                            <note>A book on the rites and observances of the Muslim creed, according
                                to the Hanafite doctrine, adapted from the Persian work, by Mawlānā
                                ʿAbd al-ʿazīzī Fārisī, but greatly enlarged and extended. The
                                Turkish translator's name is ʿAbdürraḥmān bin Yūsuf el-Aḳsarayī (see
                                fol. 5a, ln. 7, 8 and 12-14), and he completed this work according
                                to the chronogram at the end of the book on fol. 182a, ln. 8: لذکر
                                دو شدی تاریخی لمفخر ده اكا اداش, A. H. 950=A.D. 1543/1544. Copies of
                                the Persian original are noticed in Fleischer, Dresden Cat., No.
                                119, On I, and in W. Pertsch, Berlin Persian Cat., p. 241. the
                                Turkish translation see H. Khalfa iv. p. 256, No. 8303; Rieu, pp. 12
                                and 13; W. Pertsch, No. 61, and Berlin Cat., pp. 126 and 127; J.
                                Aumer, p. 7; Fleischer, Dresden Cat., No. 163, and Cat. Lips., No.
                                222; Landauer, Strassburg Cat., p. 42, No. 1, etc. Contents:
                                Muḳaddime, on fol. 5a, last line. Kitābü l-īmān (کتاب الایمان), on
                                faith, on fol. 8a. Kitābü ṣ-ṣalāt (کتاب الصلات), on prayer, on fol.
                                21a. Kitābü ṣ-ṣavm (l), on fasting, on fol. 77b. Kitābü z-zekāt
                                (کتاب الزکات), on alms, on fol. 114b. Kitābü l-ḥacc (کتاب الحج) on
                                pilgrimage, on fol. 120b. To these five sections of the Persian
                                original there are added here several new chapters, for which see
                                Fleischer, Dresden Cat., and Rieu, loc. cit. The subdivisions are
                                bābs, faṣls, and mes̠'eles. Beginning of the book on fol. 4b: الحمد
                                لله ربّ العالمين الرحمن الرحیم مالك یوم الدين اياك نعبد الخ. At the
                                end the same enumeration of authorities, consulted both by the
                                Persian author and the Turkish translator, as in Fleischer's,
                                Rieu's, and W. Pertsch's copies. A full index on ff. 1b-3a. Ff. 7
                                and 8 are a little injured at the bottom. Dated by Muṣṭafā bin
                                el-Ḥācī Muḥammed in the middle of Muḥarrem, A.H. 1045=A.D. 1635,
                                beginning of July.</note>
